\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
X-rays 
\emph default
are ideal to analyze the molecular structure of various materials.
 This is important for symmetry considerations of crystals, like determining
 the 
\emph on
Brillouin zones
\emph default
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{brillouin}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or the 
\emph on
electronic band structure 
\emph default

\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{band}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph on
.

\emph default
 Knowing the crystal structure (lattice type, lattice parameter, etc.) is
 necessary to derive physical properties of highly symmetric materials;
 e.g.
 thermal and electrical conductivity of semiconductors, melting point of
 metals, and many more.
 This knowledge can be used to built special types of conductors and semiconduct
ors, thermal isolators and even microchips 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{chip}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aim of this paper is to outline the experimental determination of two
 inorganic materials with the 
\emph on
powder diffractometry 
\emph default
technique using X-rays as interacting waves.
 There are in principle two most common methods used to determine the lattice
 type and parameter of a crystal.
 The 
\emph on
rotating crystal method 
\emph default

\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{diffraction}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph on
 
\emph default
uses samples of a macroscopic crystal, which is rotated with respect a detector
 in such a way that reflections are observed.
 In this experiment we are making use of the 
\emph on
Debye-Scherrer method
\emph default
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{diffraction}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which is a powder diffractometry technique.
 The material has to be in powder form, but is very convenient as the crystal's
 diffraction pattern does not change while the sample is rotating.

\emph on
 
\emph default
These diffractions occur only on specific planes, if the incident ray is
 at an certain angle with respect to the plane.
 Each of these planes can be labeled by the so-called 
\emph on
Miller indices
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $(hkl)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{miller}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 These angles 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{hkl}$
\end_inset

 can be calculated assuming cubic-lattice-structure on plugging the following
 equation for the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{hkl}$
\end_inset

 between the 
\begin_inset Formula $(hkl)$
\end_inset

-planes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{hkl}=\frac{a}{\sqrt{h^{2}+k^{2}+l^{2}}}\,,\label{eq:dhl}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the lattice parameter, into equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{hkl}=\arcsin(\frac{\lambda}{2\,d_{hkl}})\,,\label{eq:thetahkl}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the wavelength of radiation.
 The intensity of reflections 
\begin_inset Formula $hkl$
\end_inset

 are proportional to the 
\emph on
structure factor 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{hkl}=\sum_{\alpha}f_{\alpha}\exp(i\,\vec{K}_{hkl}\cdot\vec{r}_{\alpha})\,,\label{eq:structure}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\emph default
where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
atomic form factor
\emph default
.
 Eq.
\begin_inset Formula $\,$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dhl"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:thetahkl"

\end_inset

 are mostly responsible for the geometrical properties (independent of material
 composition), whereas 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:structure"

\end_inset

 determines the basis of unit cells.
 More theory on diffraction can be found in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{fkp}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

