\begin_layout Standard
Interatomic distance in materials are of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\unit[1-10]{\mathring{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 To investigate such tiny scales with high accuracy, electromagnetic waves
 of wavelengths in the same order of magnitude are essential.
 Such high energetic waves are called 
\emph on
X-rays
\emph default
, which are far beyond the visible spectrum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our experiment we used the most common source of X-rays: an 
\emph on
X-ray tube
\emph default
 (device: Philips PW 1729; detailed information on functionality and design
 can be obtained from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{xray}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{xraywiki}
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 In order to make a precise statement on Bragg-reflections 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{fkp}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in the diffraction spectrum of a material, we needed rays coming out of
 the tube at a precisely specified wavelength.
 The tube we used was emitting 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 spectral lines of copper.
 Thus, after placing a nickel filter in the ray-pathway before the sample,
 we got a 
\emph on
monochromatic source
\emph default
 with frequency of the 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 line.
 In our setup we operated the tube with an acceleration voltage of 
\begin_inset Formula $\unit[30]{kV}$
\end_inset

 and a current of 
\begin_inset Formula $\unit[30]{mA}$
\end_inset

.
 Altogether yield X-rays of wavelength 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\unit[1.5406]{\mathring{A}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The technique we used in our experiment is called 
\emph on
powder diffractometry 
\emph default

\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{diffraction}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph on
.
 
\emph default
The X-ray source remains fixed as the detector moves in a circle around
 the sample placed in the center of the rotational plane.
 While the detector is revolving, measuring the intensity of the diffracted
 X-ray, the sample also rotates about its axis.
 A sketch of the setup is shown in Fig.
\begin_inset Formula $\,$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Powder-diffractometry"

\end_inset

.
 We used samples in powder form (contains a huge amount of microscopic grains
 with properties of a large crystal) leaving the diffraction pattern unaltered,
 and simultaneously averaging over all possible sample orientations due
 to the sample's rotation.
 So, only the detector was moving, scanning the diffraction pattern.
 This method is called 
\emph on
Debye-Scherrer method
\emph default
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{diffraction}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

