\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this experiment we conducted 
\emph on
X-ray diffraction analysis
\emph default
 on two materials in powder form.
 The goal was to determine their chemical composition.
 This was achieved by the 
\emph on
Debye-Scherrer method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we used a Silicon sample to calibrate our X-ray device.
 The offset 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\emph{measured angle - true angle}}$
\end_inset

 came to be 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.25\pm0.01)$
\end_inset

°.
 Afterwards, the diffraction spectrum of each sample was measured.
 The appropriate 
\begin_inset Formula $hkl$
\end_inset

 reflections were inferred from the relations between the relative position
 of the observed peaks.
 Proposing several lattice types and matching the expected reflections with
 the observed ones yielded the respective lattice.
 For both samples we found a fcc crystal structure and lattice parameters
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\textrm{NaCl}}=\unit[(5.647\pm0.004)]{\mathring{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\textrm{Al}}=\unit[(4.055\pm0.006)]{\mathring{A}}$
\end_inset

 for table salt NaCl and Aluminum Al respectively.
 The final step was to qualitatively analyze the intensities of vivid 
\begin_inset Formula $(hkl)$
\end_inset

's.
 In general, irregular maxima are due to basis of unit cell containing more
 then one element, as one can deduce from the structure factor 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:structure"

\end_inset

.
 Despite seeing this only for the first reflection 
\begin_inset Formula $(111)$
\end_inset

, as others were damped by inelastic diffraction, we managed to identify
 the first sample to be NaCl by matching with data from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{database}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The second sample had no such exceptionally behavior.
 After consulting 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{database}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we found the second sample being Aluminum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We saw that powder diffractometry, especially the
\emph on
 
\emph default
Debye-Scherre method,
\emph on
 
\emph default
provides a reliable way to determine the lattice type and parameters of
 simple crystal structures.
 The obtained results can be used for other experiments, which deal with
 Al or NaCl; e.g.
 in angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy to probe electronic band structure
s.
\end_layout

